ouse<br />\nGreen Lane<br />\nDurham<br />\nDH1 3UW</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>They will look at your case and forward it to the rent assessment panel in your area.</p>\n\n<h2>Get help and advice</h2>\n\n<p>You can get help and advice from Shelter or the Residential Property Tribunal Service:</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Shelter</strong>  </p>\n\n<p>0808 800 4444</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Residential Property Tribunal Service</strong>  </p>\n\n<p>0845 600 3178</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>How the committee makes its decision</h2>\n\n<p>The committee may ask for:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>more information - eg what you think the rent should be and why</li>\n  <li>permission to inspect the property</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You may have to go to a hearing, with your landlord, to tell the committee why you think the rent is too high.</p>\n\n<p>If you and your landlord agree, the committee can decide on the case without a hearing, using written evidence.</p>\n\n<h2>The committee&rsquo;s decision</h2>\n\n<p>The committee will send its decision in writing, saying:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>what the rent should be</li>\n  <li>the date the rent is payable from</li>\n  <li>the reasons for their decision</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>If you disagree with the committee&rsquo;s decision</h2>\n\n<p>The only way to challenge the committee’s decision is through the High Court.</p>\n\n<p>If you wish to do this, you may want to <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://legaladviserfinder.justice.gov.uk/AdviserSearch.do\" title=\"Legal adviser finder\">get legal advice.</a></p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You have to appeal to the High Court within 28 days of getting the full reasons for the committee’s decision.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/housing-tribunals/leasehold-valuation-tribunal-changes-to-your-lease","slug":"leasehold-valuation-tribunal-changes-to-your-lease","order":2,"title":"Leasehold Valuation Tribunal: changes to your lease","body":"<p>If you&rsquo;re a leaseholder, you can appeal to the Leasehold Valuation Tribunal if you disagree with changes to your lease, including:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>service charges</li>\n  <li>extending a lease</li>\n  <li>buying the freehold</li>\n  <li>insuring the building</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The tribunal is independent, and can decide if a charge is too high or unreasonable, or if changes to the lease are fair.</p>\n\n<h2>Appeal to the tribunal</h2>\n\n<p>To apply to the tribunal, fill in the appropriate <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/global/forms/hmcts/tribunals/residential-property/index.htm\" title=\"Residential Property Tribunal forms\">application form</a> under the heading &lsquo;Leasehold disputes&rsquo;.</p>\n\n<p>Send the form to your <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/global/contacts/hmcts/tribunals/residential-property.htm\" title=\"Residential Property Tribunal contacts\">local rent assessment panel.</a></p>\n\n<h2>Cost of appealing to the tribunal</h2>\n\n<p>You may have to pay a fee if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you&rsquo;re appealing against a service or administration charge</li>\n  <li>the case goes to a hearing</li>\n</ul>\n\n<table>\n  <thead>\n    <tr>\n      <th><strong>Service or administration charge - amount in dispute</strong></th>\n      <th><strong>Tribunal fee</strong></th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td>£500 or less</td>\n      <td>£50</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>£500 to £1,000</td>\n      <td>£70</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>£1,000 to £5,000</td>\n      <td>£100</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>£5,000 to £15,000</td>\n      <td>£200</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>£15,000 or more</td>\n      <td>£350</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Taking the case to a hearing costs £150.</p>\n\n<p>You can pay by postal order or cheque (payable to &lsquo;HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service&rsquo;).</p>\n\n<h2>Help paying costs</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re on benefits, like Income Support, you can ask for help with your fees, using the form below:</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/global/forms/tribunals/residential-property/lvt1-reduction-waiver-fees.doc\" title=\"Download 'Application for reduction or waiver of fees' (DOC, 266KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Application for reduction or waiver of fees’ (DOC, 266KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Get help and advice</h2>\n\n<p>You can get help and advice from the Leasehold Advisory Service or the Residential Property Tribunal Service:</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Leasehold Advisory Service</strong>  </p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://clients.lease-advice.org/Default.aspx\" title=\"Online enquiry form\" rel=\"external\">Online enquiry form</a><br />\n0845 600 3178</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Residential Property Tribunal Service</strong>  </p>\n\n<p>0845 600 3178</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>What happens after you send your appeal</h2>\n\n<p>The tribunal may ask for:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>more information - eg a copy of the lease</li>\n  <li>permission to inspect the property</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You may have to go to a hearing with the freeholder.</p>\n\n<p>If there isn&rsquo;t a hearing, the tribunal will ask you to send written evidence.</p>\n\n<p>The tribunal will send you a letter giving its decision (usually within 6 weeks of any hearing).</p>\n\n<h2>If you disagree with the tribunal&rsquo;s decision</h2>\n\n<p>You may be able to appeal against the decision to a higher tribunal, called the Upper Tribunal (Lands Chamber).</p>\n\n<p>To do this, you have to ask the Leasehold Valuation Tribunal for permission to appeal, using the form below:</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/global/forms/tribunals/residential-property/lvt-permission.doc\" title=\"Download 'Application to the leasehold valuation tribunal for permission to appeal a decision of the tribunal to the Upper Tribunal (Lands Chamber)' (DOC, 123KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Application to the leasehold valuation tribunal for permission to appeal a decision of the tribunal to the Upper Tribunal (Lands Chamber)’ (DOC, 123KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You must send this form to your local rent assessment panel within 21 days of getting its decision.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Find out more about appealing to the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/guidance/courts-and-tribunals/tribunals/lands/index.htm\" title=\"Lands Tribunal guidance\">Upper Tribunal (Lands Chamber).</a></p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/housing-tribunals/residential-property-tribunal-council-homes-and-park-homes","slug":"residential-property-tribunal-council-homes-and-park-homes","order":3,"title":"Residential Property Tribunal: council homes and park homes","body":"<p>The Residential Property Tribunal can help solve disagreements about:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>council homes</li>\n  <li>park homes (static caravans or mobile homes)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Council homes</h2>\n\n<p>You can appeal to the tribunal if you disagree with a decision about your council home, eg to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>reuse an empty building</li>\n  <li>improve parts of a building</li>\n  <li>demolish or close a building</li>\n  <li>make a property safe</li>\n  <li>restrict how many people live in a property</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also appeal if you&rsquo;re refused the &lsquo;Right to Buy&rsquo; your council or housing association home because it&rsquo;s suitable for elderly people.</p>\n\n<h2>Park homes</h2>\n\n<p>You can appeal to the tribunal if you disagree with a decision about your park home - eg to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>change or end a residence agreement</li>\n  <li>change the pitch fee</li>\n  <li>move a park home</li>\n  <li>repair a park home</li>\n  <li>transfer a park home to someone else</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Appealing to the tribunal</h2>\n\n<p>To make an appeal to the tribunal, you have to fill in an <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/global/forms/hmcts/tribunals/residential-property/index.htm\" title=\"Residential Property Tribunal forms\">application form.</a></p>\n\n<p>The forms are listed under the headings:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>&lsquo;Housing Act appeals and applications&rsquo;</li>\n  <li>‘Right to Buy appeals’</li>\n  <li>‘Park homes’</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Send the form to your <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/global/contacts/hmcts/tribunals/residential-property.htm\" title=\"Residential Property Tribunal contacts\">local rent assessment panel.</a></p>\n\n<h2>Cost of appealing to the tribunal</h2>\n\n<p>You may have to pay a £150 fee for some cases. The application form will tell you if you have to pay a fee.</p>\n\n<p>You can pay by postal order or cheque (made payable to &lsquo;HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service&rsquo;).</p>\n\n<h2>Help paying costs</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re on benefits, like Income Support, you can ask for help with your fees, using the form below:</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/global/forms/tribunals/residential-property/rpt2-waiver-fees.doc\" title=\"Download 'Application for reduction or waiver of fees' (DOC, 266KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Application for reduction or waiver of fees’ (DOC, 266KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Get help and advice</h2>\n\n<p>You can get help and advice from your local Citizens Advice Bureau or the Residential Property Tribunal Service:</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Citizens Advice</strong>  </p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.citizensadvice.org.uk/index/getadvice.htm\" title=\"Citizens Advice\" rel=\"external\">Citizens Advice</a><br />\n0844 411 1444 (England)<br />\n0844 477 2020 (Wales)</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Residential Property Tribunal Service</strong>  </p>\n\n<p>0845 600 3178</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>What happens after you send your appeal</h2>\n\n<p>The tribunal may ask you for permission to inspect the property or park home.</p>\n\n<p>You may have to go to a hearing with the council or site owner.</p>\n\n<p>If there isn&rsquo;t a hearing, the tribunal will ask you to send written evidence.</p>\n\n<p>The tribunal will send you a letter giving its decision, usually shortly after any hearing.</p>\n\n<h2>If you disagree with the tribunal&rsquo;s decision</h2>\n\n<p>You may be able to appeal against the decision to a higher tribunal, called the Upper Tribunal (Lands Chamber).</p>\n\n<p>To do this, you have to ask the Residential Property Tribunal for permission to appeal, using the form below:</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/global/forms/tribunals/residential-property/rpt-permission-jun-11.doc\" title=\"Download 'Application to the Residential Property Tribunal for permission to appeal a decision to the Upper Tribunal (Lands Chamber)' (DOC, 123KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Application to the Residential Property Tribunal for permission to appeal a decision to the Upper Tribunal (Lands Chamber)’ (DOC, 123KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You must send this form to your local rent assessment panel within 21 days of getting its decision.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Find out more about appealing to the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/guidance/courts-and-tribunals/tribunals/lands/index.htm\" title=\"Lands Tribunal guidance\">Upper Tribunal (Lands Chamber).</a></p>\n"}]},"tags":[{"title":"Courts, sentencing and tribunals","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/justice%2Fcourts-sentencing-tribunals.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Attending courts, paying fines, appealing a sentence and tribunals","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=justice%2Fcourts-sentencing-tribunals","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/justice/courts-sentencing-tribunal